uggles within the vast social, cultural, and political transformations that took place during the period. The book demonstrates that an examination of that conflict within feminist history is crucial in order to understand what radical resistance meant in the face of women-centered authority.  aDescription based on information from publisher. 0aJapanxHistoryyMeiji period, 1868-1912. 0aWomenxEducationzJapanxHistory.00aShoÌ„ken,cEmpress, consort of Meiji, Emperor of Japan,d1850-1914.10aNakajima, ShoÌ„en,d1863-1901.10aShimoda, Utako,d1854-1936. 0aJapanxSocial life and customsy1868-1912. 4aElectronic books.22aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)eissuing body. 0aMichigan monograph series in Japanese studies ;v[86].40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9856453